content:
We've settled on a pattern for crystallizing signal chains into decisions. When a stream message contains a proposal (detected by DeepSeek intent classifier), the system auto-creates a draft decision node in the graph. The draft is linked to the source message and any referenced KB items. After 3 upvotes or a manual confirm from the author, the draft becomes a crystallized decision. This is stored as a new edge type 'CRYSTALLIZED_FROM' in the graph DB. We're using a background Celery task to batch-process pending drafts every 5 minutes. Found that immediate crystallization caused too many false positives during high-velocity chat periods. The 5-min delay gives time for follow-up messages to clarify or retract.

Code snippet for the Celery task:
```python
@app.task(bind=True, max_retries=3)
def crystallize_pending(self):
    pending = db.query(DraftDecision).filter(
        DraftDecision.status == 'pending',
        DraftDecision.created_at < utcnow() - timedelta(minutes=5)
    ).all()
    for draft in pending:
        if draft.upvotes >= 3 or draft.author_confirmed:
            draft.crystallize()
```
